---
/**
 * Yasothon — the inaugural Layer 2 editorial piece.
 *
 * Layout: 680px editorial column (Plex Serif body, drop cap on opening
 * paragraph) + a sticky score sidebar that surfaces the algorithmic
 * numbers without ever being overwritten by editorial framing.
 *
 * The editorial copy below is a TEMPLATE structure. Will replaces these
 * paragraphs with real field notes after the 8-10 May 2026 trip.
 * Algorithmic content (composite, category scores, rank, indicators)
 * pulls from scores.json — same source as /en/yasothon/.
 */
import Site from '../../../../layouts/Site.astro';
import ProvenanceChip from '../../../../components/ProvenanceChip.astro';
import ScorePrimitive from '../../../../components/ScorePrimitive.astro';
import Lucide from '../../../../components/Lucide.astro';
import scoresData from '../../../../data/scores.json';
import type { ScoresFile } from '../../../../data/types';
import { CATEGORIES, CATEGORY_ORDER, regionLabel } from '../../../../data/lookups';

const data = scoresData as ScoresFile;
const province = data.provinces.find((p) => p.id === 'yasothon');

if (!province) {
  // Build-time fail-loud — Yasothon should always be in the dataset.
  throw new Error('Yasothon not found in scores.json. Cannot render editorial.');
}

const region = regionLabel(province.region, 'en');
const cats = CATEGORY_ORDER.map((id) => ({
  id,
  meta: CATEGORIES[id],
  score: province.categories[id].score,
  indicatorCount: province.categories[id].indicator_count,
}));

const strongest = [...cats].sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score)[0];
const weakest = [...cats].sort((a, b) => a.score - b.score)[0];
---
<Site
  title="Yasothon, on the data and in person · Thailand Liveability Index"
  description={`Layer 2 editorial — Yasothon's TLI composite is ${province.composite}, rank ${province.rank} of 77. Field notes from May 2026 alongside the algorithmic score.`}
  locale="en"
  canonicalPath="/en/editorial/yasothon/"
  ogImage="/og/yasothon.png"
>
  <article class="editorial">
    <header class="editorial__head">
      <p class="tli-eyebrow">Layer 2 Editorial · Province Field Notes</p>
      <h1 class="editorial__title">Yasothon, on the data and in person</h1>
      <p class="editorial__byline">
        By <strong>Will Reynolds</strong> · <time datetime="2026-05-10">10 May 2026</time>
      </p>
      <p class="editorial__lede">
        Yasothon ranks <strong>{province.rank} of 77</strong> on the TLI composite —
        composite <span class="tli-num">{province.composite}</span> of 100. The number
        sits in the bottom third of the distribution, but the categories underneath it
        tell a more interesting story than the headline. This is what three days on
        the ground there did and didn't change about how I read the data.
      </p>
      <div class="editorial__meta">
        <ProvenanceChip variant="fresh" icon="calendar">FIELD VISIT 8–10 MAY 2026</ProvenanceChip>
        <ProvenanceChip icon="badge-check">NAMED BYLINE · NOT FACTORED INTO SCORES</ProvenanceChip>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="editorial__body">
      <div class="editorial__prose">
        <section class="editorial__section">
          <p class="editorial__draft-note">
            <strong>This is a template.</strong> The body below is the structural
            scaffolding for the field-notes piece — section flow, voice register,
            and the algorithmic spine the editorial sits beside. Real prose
            replaces these paragraphs after the May trip. The score panel and
            citation row use real data and ship as-is.
          </p>

          <p class="editorial__lead-para">
            <span class="editorial__dropcap">Y</span>asothon is one of the smaller
            provinces in the Northeast — under 530,000 residents, the second-smallest
            in Isan after Nong Bua Lam Phu. Its TLI composite of <span class="tli-num">{province.composite}</span> sits in the bottom
            third of the distribution. The number is doing what it should: it is the
            geometric mean of seven independent inputs, two of which are weak enough
            to drag the composite down even where other categories are credible.
            Walking through the markets and the rocket-festival district doesn't change
            what the math says. It changes what the math feels like, and what it
            doesn't capture.
          </p>

          <p>
            The strongest signal in the data is safety. Yasothon scores
            <span class="tli-num">{strongest.score}</span> in <em>{strongest.meta.label_en}</em> — driven
            by ACLED's near-zero conflict-fatality rate and a low events-per-capita number
            in the 5-year window. This is not "feels safe" tourist intuition; it's the
            same instrument that floors Pattani at 0. It is consistent with what walking
            around at night in Yasothon Town tells you. The data and the place agree.
          </p>
        </section>

        <h2 class="editorial__h2">What the weakest categories are actually measuring</h2>
        <section class="editorial__section">
          <p>
            The weakest signal is <em>{weakest.meta.label_en}</em> at <span class="tli-num">{weakest.score}</span>.
            That number's underlying indicator on the algorithmic page is the one to
            look at — not as an indictment of the place, but as a lens on what TLI is
            and isn't measuring.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>[Field-notes paragraph: what does the weakest category actually look
            like in the place — markets, employment patterns, what people said when
            asked about cost-of-living. Honest framing: the indicator is a real
            measure of what it measures, and the methodology page documents what it
            doesn't.]</em>
          </p>
        </section>

        <h2 class="editorial__h2">Where the algorithmic score is right, and where it leaves things out</h2>
        <section class="editorial__section">
          <p>
            <em>[Field-notes paragraph: places where the data and the place agree
            (e.g. economy is genuinely thin), places where the data omits real
            texture (e.g. food culture, festival economy that TAT events-per-100k
            picks up only crudely), places where the indicator framework isn't yet
            granular enough to surface what's there.]</em>
          </p>
          <figure class="editorial__figure">
            <div class="editorial__photo-placeholder">
              <span>PHOTOGRAPH · DAYLIT · DOCUMENTARY</span>
              <span class="editorial__photo-meta">Caption + as-of date · CC BY 4.0 attribution</span>
            </div>
            <figcaption>
              Field photograph from 8–10 May 2026.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </section>

        <h2 class="editorial__h2">The methodology has a known limitation here</h2>
        <section class="editorial__section">
          <p>
            <em>[Field-notes paragraph: the limitation TLI v1.0 most clearly shows
            in Yasothon — possibly that "Cost &amp; Economy" combines two genuinely
            distinct things into one indicator slot, and that GPP-per-capita
            doesn't capture informal economy depth. Honest about what would need
            to change in v1.1 and what stays in v1.0.]</em>
          </p>
        </section>

        <h2 class="editorial__h2">What an honest reader should take away</h2>
        <section class="editorial__section">
          <p>
            <em>[Closing paragraph: synthesis. The composite is correct in its math;
            it isn't dishonest about what it measures; the place has texture that no
            seven-category index will ever fully capture; the editorial layer exists
            specifically to make this gap visible without softening the algorithmic
            score.]</em>
          </p>
        </section>

        <footer class="editorial__refs">
          <p class="editorial__refs-note">
            <Lucide name="badge-check" size={12} class="tli-citations__icon" />
            This editorial sits <strong>beside</strong> the algorithmic score, not
            above it. The composite, category scores, and indicators surface in their
            own provenance-chained UI on the
            <a href={`/en/${province.id}/`} class="editorial__link">province page</a>
            and on the home page. No editorial framing here factors back into the
            scores; that is a load-bearing methodological commitment.
          </p>
        </footer>
      </div>

      <aside class="editorial__sidebar" aria-label="Algorithmic score panel">
        <div class="editorial__sidebar-inner">
          <p class="tli-eyebrow editorial__sidebar-eyebrow">Algorithmic score</p>
          <h2 class="editorial__sidebar-title">{province.name_en}</h2>
          <p class="editorial__sidebar-meta">
            <span lang="th">{province.name_th}</span> · {region} · {province.population.toLocaleString('en-US')}
          </p>

          <div class="editorial__sidebar-composite">
            <ScorePrimitive
              score={province.composite ?? 0}
              scale="hero"
              floored={province.floored}
              locale="en"
            />
            <p class="editorial__sidebar-rank">
              Rank <strong>{province.rank}</strong> of 77
            </p>
          </div>

          <h3 class="editorial__sidebar-h3">By category</h3>
          <ul class="editorial__sidebar-cats">
            {cats.map((c) => (
              <li class="editorial__sidebar-cat">
                <span class="editorial__sidebar-cat-row">
                  <span class:list={['tli-cat-dot', c.meta.cssClass]} aria-hidden="true"></span>
                  <span class="editorial__sidebar-cat-label">{c.meta.label_en}</span>
                  <span class="editorial__sidebar-cat-score tli-num">{c.score}</span>
                </span>
                <span class="editorial__sidebar-cat-meta">
                  {c.indicatorCount} indicator{c.indicatorCount === 1 ? '' : 's'}
                </span>
              </li>
            ))}
          </ul>

          <a href={`/en/${province.id}/`} class="editorial__sidebar-link">
            Full province page
            <Lucide name="external-link" size={11} class="tli-link__icon" />
          </a>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </article>
</Site>
